It seems to be an issue with python 3, not AES and it seems complicated.

First of all, to_param_string() returns bytes objects in case of py3 and str objects in case of py2. 
This means that PyString_Check($input) in pykcs11.i:235 will always fail in case of py3.

Again, if this issue is fixed, SWIG_AsCharPtrAndSize doesn't work as expected in case of py3.

I was able to have everything work by making to_param_string() always return str as well as making the typemap as follows (recommended way to portably handle strings in py2 & py3):

```
%typemap(in) void* {
    char *buf;
    size_t sz;
    // If the value being set is of string type:
    if (PyUnicode_Check($input)) {
    	arg2 = PyUnicode_DATA($input);
      }
    else {
      // If the value being set is of CK_RSA_PKCS_OAEP_PARAMS type:
      int res2 = SWIG_ConvertPtr($input, &arg2, $descriptor(CK_RSA_PKCS_OAEP_PARAMS*), 0 |  0 );
      if (!SWIG_IsOK(res2)) {
        SWIG_exception_fail(SWIG_ArgError(res2), "unsupported CK_MECHANISM Parameter type.");
      }
    }
}
```

However I don't have the time to test the solution and I strongly believe it needs much more testing. Also the "CK_RSA_PKCS_OAEP_PARAMS type" is a bit of a hack.

@maxtepkeev Thanks for your response. Bundling it for compatibility sounds ok as long as you're sure that if the system has a newer version of `python-requests` that it will be used. Where in the code does it do that?

Given that, if the bundled version is insecure and the user hasn't installed `python-requests` explicitly (which would give them the secure version) then they will be vulnerable until you release a rebundled version. This is the classic tradeoff between usability and security. Systems that are perfectly secure are generally unusable. There are upsides and downsides to both. You've clearly thought it through so that is good. Since you're choosing usability, I assume you'll be following `python-requests` community closely for security vulnerabilities discovered since you'll be responsible for quickly repackaging them.

