Looks like resolver should not be a `coroutine`. However it can return `asyncio.Future` which will be executed asynchronously. And of course `Schema.execute` should be called with `return_promise=True` to get promise and execute it in your asyncio event loop. I've modified your code a bit so now it now returns `OrderedDict([('recipes', [OrderedDict([('name', 'hello')])])])` as expected.
```python
import asyncio
from graphql.execution.executors.asyncio import AsyncioExecutor
import graphene

class Recipe(graphene.ObjectType):
    name = graphene.String()

class Query(graphene.ObjectType):

    recipes = graphene.List(Recipe)

    @asyncio.coroutine
    def async_resolve_recipes(self):
        return [
            Recipe(name='hello')
        ]

    @graphene.resolve_only_args
    def resolve_recipes(self):
        return asyncio.async(self.async_resolve_recipes())


schema = graphene.Schema(
    query=Query,
    executor=AsyncioExecutor()
)

executed_promise = schema.execute("""
    query {
        recipes {
            name
        }
    }
""", return_promise=True)
executed = asyncio.get_event_loop().run_until_complete(executed_promise)

print(executed.data)
```

